\c 1
\ms1 SECTION ONE: The introduction
\mr (1:1–2:13)
\s1 Iyyov’s prosperous life
\p
\v 1 \add Once\add* there was a man called Iyyov \add (Job)\add* who lived in the Uz region. \add He\add* was blameless and righteous—both obeying God and avoiding evil.
\v 2 He had seven sons and three daughters,
\v 3 and he owned 7,000 sheep, 3,000 camels, 1,000 cattle, and 500 donkeys, as well as many slaves. Iyyov was \add richer\add* than \add anyone else\add* who lived in the area east \add of the Jordan River\add*.
\v 4 \add Iyyov’s\add* sons \add regularly\add* held feasts in their homes, and whenever any of them held a feast, he would invite all his brothers and sisters to share the meal with him.
\v 5 \add Then once a feast was over\add*, Iyyov would send \add for his children\add* and consecrate them—he got up early in the morning and offered burnt offerings for each of them, because Iyyov said, “Perhaps my \add children\add* have sinned and cursed\f + \fr 1:15 \ft Literally ‘blessed’ but it’s possible that the original reading was ‘cursed’ and that scribes changed it to ‘blessed’ in order to avoid the uncomfortable concept of a person cursing God. Traditional manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible don’t have a marginal notation about this (as they do in the case of 7:20), but LXX uses ‘ἐνενοήθησαν κακά’ which can be rendered as ‘have thought evil things’ and the Peshitta (Syriac) uses ‘reviled’. Many other translations also use ‘cursed’ since this is the kind of change that scribes are known to have made in similar cases.\f* God in their hearts.” \add It was Job’s regular habit to\add* \add intercede for his children\add*.
\s1 Satan’s first attack on Iyyov
\p
\v 6 It was the day that God’s sons\f + \fr 1:6 \ft It’s not clear from the text who these are.\f* came to present themselves to Yahweh, and the adversary (Satan) was also there among them.\x + \xo 1:6: \xt Gen 6:2.\x*
\v 7 Yahweh asked him, “Where have you just come from?”
\p “I have come from the earth, where I was travelling around \add to see what was going on\add*.” Satan replied.
\p
\v 8 “Have you \add noticed\add* my servant Iyyov?” Yahweh asked. “There’s no one else like him on the \add whole\add* earth—a blameless and righteous man who obeys me God and avoids \add anything\add* evil.”
\p
\v 9 “Does Iyyov \add get\add* nothing \add back\add* for respecting God?” Satan answered Yahweh.
\v 10 “Don’t you \add constantly protect\add* him and his household and everything that’s his? You’ve blessed \add what he works on\add*, and his \add livestock have multiplied prolifically\add*.
\v 11 However, just stretch out your hand and \add ruin\add* everything he has, then \add we’ll see that\add* he’ll curse you to your face.”
\p
\v 12 “Listen, \add I’ll cede you control over\add* everything he has,” Yahweh replied. “Only \add just\add* don’t do \add anything\add* against \add Iyyov himself\add*.” \add So\add* the adversary went away from Yahweh’s \add presence\add*.
\s1 Satan destroys Iyyov’s wealth and children
\p
\v 13 \add So one\add* day when \add Iyyov’s\add* sons and his daughters were eating and drinking wine in their eldest brother’s house,
\v 14 a messenger came to Iyyov and \add reported\add*, “\add While\add* the oxen were plowing and the donkeys were feeding \add nearby\add*,
\v 15 the Sabeans attacked with their swords and stole them \add all\add*. They killed all your slaves except that I \add managed to\add* escape to tell you.”
\p
\v 16 \add While\add* he was still speaking, another \add messenger\add* came and said, “The fire of God fell from the sky and burnt up the sheep and the \add shepherds\add*. \add Only ashes are left\add*, except that I alone escaped to tell you.”
\p
\v 17 \add While\add* he was still speaking, another \add one\add* came and \add explained\add*, “The Chaldeans formed into three bands and \add raided\add* the camels and took them, and they attacked the slaves with their swords, and I’m the only one who escaped to \add come and\add* tell you.”
\p
\v 18 \add While\add* he was still speaking, another \add messenger\add* came and said, “Your sons and daughters were eating and drinking wine in the house of their eldest brother
\v 19 when \add suddenly\add* a \add freak\add* wind came from across the desert and struck the house. It \add collapsed\add* on the young people and \add killed them\add*, and only I alone have escaped to tell you.”
\p
\v 20 Then Iyyov stood up and tore his robe and shaved his head. Then he knelt with his face to the ground and worshipped \add God\add*,
\v 21 saying, “I came naked from my mother’s womb, and I will \add leave this life\add* naked. Yahweh gave, and Yahweh has taken. May Yahweh’s \add reputation???\add* be blessed.”
\p
\v 22 \add Through\add* all of that, Iyyov didn’t \add disobey\add* God or \add accuse him of being evil\add*.
\c 2
\s1 Satan’s second attack on Iyyov
\p
\v 1 It was the day that God’s sons came to present themselves to Yahweh and the adversary (Satan) was also there among them.
\v 2 “Where have you come from?” Yahweh \add asked\add* the adversary.
\p “From wandering on the earth and going back and forth on it,” \add he\add* answered.
\p
\v 3 “Have you \add noticed\add* my servant Iyyov \add (Job)\add*?” Yahweh asked Satan, “because there’s no one like him on the earth—a blameless and righteous man, \add striving to obey\add* God and turning from evil. And he’s still holding firmly to his integrity, even though you incited me against him, to \add ruin\add* him for nothing.”
\p
\v 4 “Skin for skin,” replied the adversary, “\add actually, a person will give everything they have to save their\add* life.
\v 5 However, just \add reach out\add* and touch his flesh and bones, \add and see\add* if he doesn’t curse you to your face.”
\p
\v 6 “\add Listen\add*,” Yahweh said to \add him\add*, “\add I’ll give you power over him\add*, but you \add must\add* preserve his life.”
\p
\v 7 So the adversary went away from Yahweh’s \add presence\add*, and he \add infected\add* Iyyov with bad boils from the sole of his foot to \add the top of his head\add*.
\v 8 \add Iyyov picked up a piece of broken pottery\add* to \add scratch\add* himself with \add as\add* he sat \add down\add* in the middle of a pile of ashes.
\p
\v 9 “Are you still holding tightly onto your integrity?” his wife \add asked\add* him. “\add Just\add* curse God and die.”
\p
\v 10 “You’re talking like a foolish \add person\add*,” Iyyov \add replied\add*. “Should we \add only\add* accept good from God and not receive the bad?” In all of that, Iyyov didn’t sin \add in what he said\add*.
\s1 Iyyov’s three friends come
\p
\v 11 \add When\add* Iyyov’s three friends heard \add about all the troubles that had happened to\add* him, they each came from his place: Elifaz from Teman, Bildad from Shuah, and Zofar from Naamah. They gathered together to come to console and comfort him.
\v 12 \add but when\add* they saw him from a distance, they \add barely\add* recognised him. They \add wailed loudly\add*, and they \add ripped their own clothes\add*, and they threw dust \add into the air so that it would fall\add* on their heads. \add (All three of those were traditional signs of mourning.)\add*
\v 13 Then they sat with him \add there\add* on the ground for seven days and seven nights without saying a \add single\add* word to \add Iyyov\add* because they had seen that \add his\add* suffering was extreme.
\c 3
\ms1 SECTION TWO: Iyyov talking with his friends
\mr (3:1–27:33)
\s1 Iyyov’s complaint
\p
\v 1 After that, Iyyov spoke up and cursed \add the\add* day \add of\add* his \add conception\add*.\x + \xo 3:1-19: \xt Jer 20:14-18.\x*
\p
\v 2 He said:
\q1
\v 3 May the day on which I was born perish,
\q1 and the night that said, ‘A boy has been conceived.’
\q1
\v 4 May that day be dark.
\q1 May God not search for it from above
\q2 and may no light shine on it.
\q1
\v 5 May darkness and a dark shadow claim it.
\q1 May a cloud remain over it.
\q1 May the blacknesses of the day terrify it.
\q1
\v 6 May gloom take that night.
\q1 May it not be happy among the days of the year.
\q1 May it not enter into the number of months.
\q1
\v 7 Listen, may that night be barren.
\q1 May a happy shout never enter it.
\q1
\v 8 May those who curse days, curse that one—
\q1 \add yes,\add* those \add people\add* who’re skillful enough to wake up the large sea monster.
\q1
\v 9 May the stars of its twilight be dark.
\q1 May it stay waiting for the light that never \add arrives\add*.
\q1 May it not see the dawn \add breaking\add*.
\q1
\v 10 Because it didn’t close the doors of my \add mother’s\add* womb,
\q1 to hide the sorrow from my eyes.
\b
\q1
\v 11 Why didn’t I die \add at birth\add*?
\q1 \add Just\add* come out then stop breathing?
\q1
\v 12 Why was I accepted onto \add her lap\add*?
\q1 And onto those breasts to suckle?
\q1
\v 13 \add Yes,\add* I’d be peacefully lying down now.
\q1 I would have slept and been at rest,
\q1
\v 14 along with kings and counsellors of the earth—
\q1 \add yes,\add* those who built monuments for themselves.
\q1
\v 15 Or \add been asleep\add* with princes \add and their\add* gold—
\q1 those who filled their houses with silver.
\q1
\v 16 I might never have been—like a stillborn child.
\q1 Like some infants who never see the light.
\q1
\v 17 Wicked \add people\add* don’t cause any more trouble there.
\q1 Those who’ve run out of strength rest there.
\q1
\v 18 Prisoners are able to relax together.
\q1 They no longer hear the voice of their taskmaster.
\q1
\v 19 Ordinary and famous \add people are all\add* alike there.
\q1 And slaves \add there\add* no longer have \add to obey their\add* masters.
\b
\q1
\v 20 Why is light given to \add those\add* who’re miserable?
\q1 And why’s life \add given to those\add* who’re bitter inside?
\q1
\v 21 They wish for death but it won’t come.\x + \xo 3:21: \xt Rev 9:6.\x*
\q1 They dig for it more than for hidden treasure.
\q1
\v 22 Those who’re happy for happiness sake,
\q1 will celebrate when they find the grave.
\q1
\v 23 \add Why search for\add* a path that’s hidden
\q2 when God has hedged them in?
\b
\q1
\v 24 Sighing has \add become more important\add* than eating.
\q1 My groans \add just\add* pour out like water.
\q1
\v 25 I had my fears and they’ve \add come to pass\add*.
\q1 What I dreaded has come to me.
\q1
\v 26 I’m not relaxed or peaceful.
\q1 I can’t rest \add because only\add* trouble comes.
\c 4
\s1 Elifaz’s first response to Iyyov
\sr (4:1–14:22)
\p
\v 1 Then Elifaz (from Teman) \add replied\add*:
\q1
\v 2 If \add someone\add* tries \add to talk\add* with you, will it wear you out?
\q1 \add But\add* who can resist \add answering\add*?
\q1
\v 3 Listen, you’ve instructed many \add other people\add*.
\q1 And you’ve \add encouraged those who were\add* weak.
\q1
\v 4 Your words have encouraged those who were stumbling.
\q1 You’ve strengthened \add those\add* whose knees were buckling.
\q1
\v 5 But now it’s you \add in trouble\add* and you’re \add depressed\add*.
\q1 \add Troubles\add* touch you and you’re discouraged.
\q1
\v 6 Doesn’t your \add faith\add* give you confidence?
\q1 \add What about\add* your hope and your integrity?
\q1
\v 7 Remember: Who has \add ever\add* perished when they were innocent?\f + \fr 4:7 \ft Don’t forget that this is Elifaz giving his opinions and advice, and not necessarily endorsed as theologically sound. See God’s disapproval of the words of Elifaz and his companions in Job 42:7-8.\f*
\q1 Or when were godly people \add ever\add* destroyed?
\b
\q1
\v 8 Just like I’ve seen those who plant evil and sow mischief harvest it \add back again\add*,
\q1
\v 9 God’s breath \add causes\add* them to perish,
\q1 and with a snort of his nose they come to an end.
