\c 38
\ms1 SECTION SIX: God’s speeches
\mr (38:1–42:6)
\s1 God answers Iyyov
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh answered Iyyov from the storm:
\q1
\v 2 Who is this giving \add bad advice\add*,
\q1 with words that are lacking knowledge?
\q1
\v 3 \add Get ready to battle\add*\f + \fr 38:3 \ft Lit. ‘Gird your loins’. In a robe-wearing culture, it was normal for a man to tuck the bottom of his robe up into his belt to clear his legs to be able to move more freely—perhaps to run, but also to fight.\f*like a man,
\q1 and I’ll question you and you can answer me.
\b
\q1
\v 4 Where were you when I laid \bd the world’s foundations\bd*?
\q1 Do tell me, if you understand that.
\q1
\v 5 Who decided on it’s measurements, if you know?
\q1 Or who stretched out a tape measure over it?
\q1
\v 6 What were its footings attached to?
\q1 Who put its reference stone in place
\q1
\v 7 when the morning stars sung together,
\q1 and God’s children shouted happily?
\b
\q1
\v 8 \add Who was\add* the one who confined \bd the ocean\bd* with gates\x + \xo 38:8-11: \xt Psa 104:9; Prv 8:29; Jer 5:22.\x*
\q1 \add when\add* it burst its way out from the womb?
\q1
\v 9 I \add covered it\add* with clouds as its clothing,
\q1 and thick darkness as its tight blanket.
\q1
\v 10 I assigned my boundaries for \add the ocean\add*,
\q1 and put a latch on its gates,
\q1
\v 11 and I said, ‘You can only come this far and no further.
\q1 Your proud waves will be stopped here.’
\b
\q1
\v 12 In all your life, have you ever commanded the morning \add to come\add*,
\q1 or helped the dawn to know its place
\q1
\v 13 so that it might take hold of the bottom edges of the earth
\q1 and shake the wicked out of it?\f + \fr 38:13 \ft Of course, the wicked are busy in the ‘blanket of darkness’, but dawn pulls that off them.\f*
\q1
\v 14 \add After dawn,\add* \add the earth\add* \add takes shape\add* like clay \add when a seal is pressed into it\add*,
\q1 and \add its features\add* stand out like folds in a cloak.
\q1
\v 15 Their light is withheld from wicked \add people\add*,
\q1 and their arm raised \add in violence\add* gets broken.
\q1
\v 16 Have you visited the springs \add under\add* the sea?
\q1 Have you walked around in the trenches of the deep \add ocean\add*?
\q1
\v 17 Have the gates of death been revealed to you?
\q1 Have you seen the gates \add that open into\add* deep darkness?
\q1
\v 18 Have you taken note of the width of the earth?
\q1 Do tell me if you know all those things.
\q1
\v 19 How do you get to where light lives,
\q1 and where is the place that darkness comes from?
\q1
\v 20 Can you take it to its territory,
\q1 and how would you figure out the paths to its house?
\q1
\v 21 You’d know because \add surely\add* you were born before then, \add ☺\add*
\q1 and you’re so very, very old. \add ☺\add*
\b
\q1
\v 22 Have you entered the warehouses where snow is stored,
\q1 and have you seen the bunker where hail is kept,
\q1
\v 23 which I keep there ready for troubled times—
\q1 for \add the\add* day of war and battle?
\q1
\v 24 Where’s the way to \add find\add* where light is distributed,
\q1 \add or where\add* the east wind gets scattered all over the earth?
\q1
\v 25 Who cuts out the channels for the downpours \add to flow in\add*,
\q1 and makes the path for thunderbolts?
\q1
\v 26 \add Who sends\add* rain to regions where nobody lives,
\q1 \add or\add* to a wilderness that has nobody in it,
\q1
\v 27 to satisfy the parched wasteland
\q1 and to cause fresh grass to shoot up?
\q1
\v 28 Does the rain have a father,
\q1 or who gave birth to the dew drops?
\q1
\v 29 ≈Whose womb does the ice come from,
\q1 and who gives birth to the frost \add that descends\add* from the sky,
\q1
\v 30 when the waters become hard like stone,
\q1 and the surface of the deep \add ocean\add* freezes?
\b
\q1
\v 31 Can you tie together \bd the \add stars\add*\bd* of Pleiades,\x + \xo 38:31: \xt Yob 9:9; Amos 5:8.\x*
\q1 or loosen Orion’s belt?
\q1
\v 32 Can you lead each constellation out in its season,
\q1 and can you guide the Bear with her cubs?
\q1
\v 33 Do you understand the physical laws of the universe,
\q1 or can you establish their rule over the earth?
\b
\q1
\v 34 Can you \add command\add* \bd the clouds\bd* with your voice,
\q1 and \add cause\add* a flood of water to cover you?
\q1
\v 35 Can you send out flashes of lightning,
\q1 \add so\add* they go off then tell you, ‘Here we are’?
\q1
\v 36 Who put wisdom into people’s minds,
\q1 or can give understanding to the mind?
\q1
\v 37 Who has \add enough\add* wisdom to number the clouds,
\q1 and who will tip over the water jars of the sky
