\q1
\v 22 It laughs at fear—not afraid at all,
\q1 and it doesn’t retreat back from the sword.
\q1
\v 23 The quiver \add of arrows\add* rattles on its side.
\q1 The spear and the javelin flash.
\q1
\v 24 Shaking with excitement, it \add speeds over\add*.
\q1 It can’t stand still once the horn is sounded.
\q1
\v 25 When it hears the horn, it snorts ready to go,
\q1 and it smells the battle from far away—
\q1 the shouts of the commanders and the battle-cries.
\b
\q1
\v 26 Is it your wisdom that the hawk uses to soar,
\q1 \add and why\add* it spreads its wings to \add migrate\add* south?
\q1
\v 27 Is it your command that sends the eagle flying upwards,
\q1 and \add tells it\add* to build it nest up so high?
\q1
\v 28 It lives on a cliff,
\q1 and spends the night in its fortress among the sharp rocks.
\q1
\v 29 From there, it spies out food.
\q1 Its eyes watch from far away.
\q1
\v 30 Its young ones feast on blood,\x + \xo 39:30: \xt Mat 24:28; Luk 17:37.\x*
\q1 and where there’s dead \add bodies\add*, they’ll be there.
\c 40
\s1 God challenges Iyyov to answer
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh \add continued\add* to speak to Iyyov:
\q1
\v 2 Will the \add person\add* who’s been finding faults \add now\add* argue with the provider?
\q1 Let the \add one\add* who \add tries to\add* correct God, give an answer.
\s1 Iyyov’s non-answer
\p
\v 3 Then Iyyov answered Yahweh:
\q1
\v 4 Indeed, I’m insignificant—what could I answer?
\q1 I’ll \add just\add* put my hand over my mouth.
\q1
\v 5 I’ve spoken once, but I won’t answer,
\q1 and twice, but I won’t continue.
\s1 God’s response to Iyyov
\p
\v 6 Then Yahweh again spoke to Iyyov from inside the storm:
\q1
\v 7 \add Now\add* tuck up your robe like a man \add going into battle\add*.
\q1 I will question you, and you must answer me.
\q1
\v 8 Would you actually invalidate my judgement?
\q1 \add Would you\add* condemn me so you can \add declare yourself\add* right?
\q1
\v 9 Is your arm \add as powerful\add* as God’s?
\q1 Can you thunder with a voice like his?
\q1
\v 10 \add Then\add* embellish yourself with majesty and greatness,
\q1 and dress yourself with honour and splendour.
\q1
\v 11 Let your fierce anger loose,
\q1 and take every proud \add person\add* on and bring them down.
\q1
\v 12 ≈Take note of every proud \add person\add* and humble them.
\q1 Crush wicked \add people\add* where they stand.
\q1
\v 13 \add Bury\add* them together in the dust.
\q1 \add Imprison them in the grave.\add*
\q1
\v 14 Then I’d even admit to you
\q1 that you \em can\em* save yourself \add with your own strength\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 15 Now look at the \bd sauropod\bd* which I made \add on the same day\add* as you.
\q1 It eats grass like a cow.
\q1
\v 16 Notice the strength in his thighs,
\q1 and the power of his stomach muscles.
\q1
\v 17 It bends its tail like a cedar tree.
\q1 Its thigh tendons are tightly strung.
\q1
\v 18 Its bones are \add like\add* bronze pipes.
\q1 Its legs are like iron rods.
\q1
\v 19 It’s \add at\add* the beginning of God’s paths. ???
\q1 The creator has let him bring his sword near. ???
\q1
\v 20 The hills provide produce for it,
\q1 and all the animals in the countryside play there.
\q1
\v 21 It lies under \add the\add* lotus trees,
\q1 hidden in the reeds in the marsh.
\q1
\v 22 The lotus trees cover it with their shade.
\q1 The poplars in the riverbed surround it.
\q1
\v 23 If the river gets violent, it doesn’t rush out.
\q1 It remains confident even when the Jordan \add River\add* surges to his mouth.
\q1
\v 24 Can anyone capture it while its eyes \add watch\add*?
\q1 Is there anyone who can \add make\add* a snare to pierce its nose?
\c 41
\p
\v 1 Can you pull \bd the sea dragon\bd* with a hook,\x + \xo 41:1: \xt Psa 74:14; 104:26; Isa 27:1.\x*
\q1 or tie his tongue down with a rope?
\q1
\v 2 Can you put a leash into its nose,
\q1 or pierce its jaw with a harpoon?
\q1
\v 3 Will it beg you over and over for mercy?
\q1 Maybe if it says tender things to you?
\q1
\v 4 Will it make an agreement with you?
\q1 Might you take it as a slave \add for the rest of its life\add*?
\q1
\v 5 Will you play with it like with a pet,
\q1 and tie it on a leash for your girls?
\q1
\v 6 Will your team set a price on \add the whole creature\add*?
\q1 Will they divide it up among the merchants?
\q1
\v 7 Can you fill its hide with harpoons,
\q1 or its head with fishing spears?
\q1
\v 8 Put your hand on it and you’ll remember the battle—
\q1 don’t do it!
\q1
\v 9 What hope would \add you\add* have against it?
\q1 Aren’t \add you\add* put off just from looking at it?
\q1
\v 10 No one’s fierce enough to wake it up,
\q1 \add so\add* how might you expect to stand up to me?
\q1
\v 11 Who has confronted me \add with any claim\add* that I should repay?
\q1 Everything under the \add sky\add* belongs to me.
\q1
\v 12 I won’t keep quiet \add about\add* its limbs,
\q1 or about its strength and the beauty of its form.
\q1
\v 13 Who can remove its armour plating at the front,
\q1 or penetrate beyond its chestplate?
\q1
\v 14 Who can open its jaws,
\q1 when there’s terror all around its teeth?
\q1
\v 15 Rows of scales are its pride,
\q1 fitting into each other with a tight seal.
\q1
\v 16 Each one is very close to the next,
\q1 and no air can get between them.
\q1
\v 17 The lock tightly to their next door neighbour.
\q1 They cling together and can’t be separated.
\q1
\v 18 Its snorting causes flashes of light,
\q1 and its eyes are like the \add early rays\add* of dawn.
\q1
\v 19 Flames come from its mouth.
\q1 Sparks of fire leap out.
\q1
\v 20 Smoke pours from its nostrils,
\q1 like a boiling pot with a \add hollow\add* reed \add in it\add*.
\q1
\v 21 Its breath sets coals on fire,
\q1 and a flame comes out of its mouth.
\q1
\v 22 There’s \add incredible\add* strength in its neck,
\q1 and fear \add always\add* goes ahead of it.
\q1
\v 23 The folds of his body are joined tightly together—
\q1 so firm that they can’t be moved.
\q1
\v 24 His chest is hard like stone—
\q1 \add yes,\add* as solid as the bottom mill-stone.
\q1
\v 25 When it rises up, even mighty \add men\add* are afraid.
\q1 They retreat if they see it thrashing around.
\q1
\v 26 Striking it with a sword would have no effect,
\q1 nor would a spear, arrow, or dart.
\q1
\v 27 Iron is like straw \add to the sea dragon\add*,
\q1 and bronze like rotten wood.
\q1
\v 28 Nothing shot with a bow can make it turn away—
\q1 For it, stones from a sling are like bits of straw.
\q1
\v 29 \add Heavy\add* clubs are just like a grain stalk,
\q1 and it laughs at the rattling of a spear.
\q1
\v 30 Its underbelly is sharp like broken pottery.
\q1 It tears up the mud like a sledge for threshing \add grain\add*.
\q1
\v 31 It makes the deep \add ocean\add* boil like a pot.
\q1 It makes the sea \add swirl\add* like a jar of ointment.
\q1
\v 32 It leaves a glistening wake behind it—
\q1 you’d think that the deep \add water\add* had white hair.
\q1
\v 33 There’s no equal to it on the earth—
\q1 the creature that was made to have no fear.
\q1
\v 34 It looks down on all \add those who think they’re powerful\add*.
\q1 It’s the king of all those who’re proud.
\c 42
\s1 Iyyov requests God’s forgiveness
\p
\v 1 Then Iyyov answered Yahweh:
\q1
\v 2 I know that you can do everything,
\q1 and no one can stop you from doing what you want.
\q1
\v 3 \add You asked,\add* \x + \xo 42:3: \xt Yob 38:2.\x*
\q2 ‘Who’s this concealing counsel without knowledge?’
\q1 That’s why I spouted out things I didn’t understand—
\q1 things that are too wonderful for me—that I didn’t know.
\q1
\v 4 Listen now, and I’ll speak.\x + \xo 42:4: \xt Yob 38:3.\x*
\q1 I’ll tell you my question and you can inform me.
\b
\q1
\v 5 I’d heard you with my \add ears\add*,
\q1 but now I can see you with my \add eyes\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Therefore I despise \add myself for what I said\add*,
\q1 and I \add show my\add* repentance \add by sitting in dust and ashes\add*.
\ms1 SECTION SEVEN: Final speech
\mr (42:7-17)
\s1 Iyyov’s three friends humiliated by God
\p
\v 7 After Yahweh had said that to Iyyov, \add he\add* told Elifaz (from Teman), “I’m angry with you and your two friends, because what you all said about me wasn’t right, like what Iyyov \add said\add*.
\v 8 \add So\add* now get seven bulls and seven rams and go to my servant Iyyov and offer \add them\add* as a burnt offering for yourselves. Then my servant Iyyov will pray for you all. \add I’ll do what he asks and\add* not deal with you like your foolishness \add deserves\add*, because you all didn’t speak accurately about me like Iyyov did.”
\p
\v 9 \add So\add* Elifaz (from Teman) and Bildad (from Shuah) and Zofar (from Naamah) went and did what Yahweh had told them, and Yahweh accepted Iyyov’s \add prayer\add*.
\s1 Iyyov’s doubled restoration
\p
\v 10 After Iyyov had prayed for his friends, Yahweh \add changed his situation\add* and \add gave\add* \add him\add* double \add what he had before\add*.\x + \xo 42:10: \xt Yob 1:1-3.\x*
\v 11 Then all of his brothers and sisters and everyone who’d known him before, came to his house and \add had a meal\add* with him, and they comforted him and consoled him about all the troubles that Yahweh had brought on him. Then they each gave him a \add silver coin\add* and a gold ring.
\p
\v 12 Then Yahweh blessed the second part of Iyyov’s \add life\add* more than the first, and he \add ended up with\add* 14,000 sheep, 6,000 camels, 1,000 \add working\add* pairs of cows, and 1,000 female donkeys.
\v 13 He \add also\add* had seven \add more\add* sons and three \add more\add* daughters
\v 14 who he named Yemimah, Ketsiah, and Keren-Happuk.
\v 15 No one in the whole country was as beautiful as Iyyov’s daughters, and as well as their brothers, their father gave them \add each a piece of land\add* as an inheritance.
\v 16 Iyyov lived another 140 years after \add all\add* that, and was \add even\add* able to see his great-grandchildren.
\v 17 Then Iyyov died \add in good circumstances\add* and at a very old age.
